Instead of using Thread.sleep, you should consider using background threads or asynchronous tasks to perform time-consuming operations. In your case, when you call OpenNotificationSettings, you are starting an Intent which may involve activities or dialogs, and these operations should not be done on the UI thread. 

Like this: 

    private void OpenNotificationSettings() {
        // Post a delayed action to run after 200ms
        new Handler().postDelayed(new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                Intent intent = new Intent(Settings.ACTION_CHANNEL_NOTIFICATION_SETTINGS);
                intent.putExtra(Settings.EXTRA_APP_PACKAGE, requireContext().getPackageName());
                intent.putExtra(Settings.EXTRA_CHANNEL_ID, &quot;task_reminder&quot;);
                startActivity(intent);
            }
        }, 200); // Delay in ms
    }

By using a Handler and postDelayed, you introduce a delay without freezing the UI thread. This should prevent the laggy ripple effect you were experiencing while ensuring a responsive user interface.

