You should be controlling the time zone / zone id this code uses, the server does not necessarily have the same one as your system.

I would do that by using `java.time` and separating the validation from any debug / info output.

Just use a method that tells you if the URL has expired or not, maybe like this:

```Java
public static boolean hasExpired(Instant urlCreatedAt, Instant now) {
	Instant urlExpiresAt = urlCreatedAt.plus(90, ChronoUnit.DAYS);
	return now.isAfter(urlExpiresAt);
}
```

Then provide some timestamps, pass them to the method, output their values in date-time style in a specific `ZoneId`:

```Java
public static void main(String[] args) {
	// provide some arbitrary url creation times
	List&lt;Long&gt; urlCreationTimes = List.of(
				1635364328794L,
				1655364328794L,
				1685364328794L,
				1695364328794L,
				1795364328794L
			);
	// get now
	Instant now = Instant.now();
	// define the zone you want to display the expiry date
	ZoneId serverZone = ZoneId.of(&quot;Australia/Brisbane&quot;);
	// check for each creation time if it has expired
	urlCreationTimes.forEach(creationTime -&gt; {
		// create an Instant from the creation timestamp
		Instant createdAt = Instant.ofEpochMilli(creationTime);
		// check if the URL has expired and print out some information
		if (hasExpired(createdAt, now)) {
			System.out.println(
				String.format(
					&quot;The Activation URL has expired on %s&quot;,
					createdAt.plus(90, ChronoUnit.DAYS)
							 .atZone(serverZone)
				   			 .format(dtfDate)
				)
			);
		} else {
			System.out.println(
				String.format(&quot;The Activation URL will expire on %s&quot;,
		   			 	createdAt.plus(90, ChronoUnit.DAYS)
								 .atZone(serverZone)
					   			 .format(dtfDate))
			);
		}
	});
}
```

This will output the *date plus offset from UTC* the URL either has expired or will expire…

```none
The Activation URL has expired on 26/01/22 (+10:00)
The Activation URL has expired on 14/09/22 (+10:00)
The Activation URL has expired on 27/08/23 (+10:00)
The Activation URL will expire on 21/12/23 (+10:00)
The Activation URL will expire on 21/02/27 (+10:00)
```

You can also use the default zone id of the system by `ZoneId.systemDefault()` on the server and on your system. They are not necessarily the same and with an offset of ten hours from UTC, there&#39;s a good chance the expiry date will differ from zone id to zone id.

