&gt; Could you give an example of the type of code I would use?

You may regret that.

First, you should start by defining some models which describe your data. This allows you to decouple your UI from your data (this is the bases of the &quot;model-view-controller&quot; concept)...
    
    public enum Biome {
        FOREST, PLAINS
    }
    
    public interface Chunk {
        public Biome getBiome();
        public Point getLocation();
    }
    
    public interface World {
        public Chunk getChunkAt(int x, int y);
    }

That&#39;s pretty basic, but we also need some way to be able to create random chunks, in this case we can use a concept of a factory...
    
    public interface ChunkFactory {
        public Chunk createChunk(Point worldLocation);
    }

&gt; But why are we using `interface`s?

Interfaces allow you to define the contracts of your code without been tied to individual implementations.  This also supports the &quot;dependency injection&quot; principle.

Next, we need to define some kind of model to store our chunks in, one which can by randomly accessed and which can dynamically grow based on the data been placed in it.

To this end, I&#39;d consider some kind of &quot;matrix&quot;.  You could use a two dimensional array, but where&#39;s the fun in that &#128521;.

The follow is a concept of a &quot;matrix&quot; backed by `Map`...

    // This basically acts a multi dimensional matrix of values, keyed by the
    // x/y coordinates.
    public interface Matrix&lt;Type&gt; {
        public Type get(int x, int y);
        public void put(Type value, int x, int y);
    }
    
    public class HashMapMatrix&lt;Type&gt; implements Matrix&lt;Type&gt; {        
        private Map&lt;Integer, Map&lt;Integer, Type&gt;&gt; values = new HashMap&lt;&gt;(8);
        
        @Override
        public Type get(int x, int y) {
            Map&lt;Integer, Type&gt; rows = values.get(y);
            if (rows == null) {
                return null;
            }
            return rows.get(x);
        }
        
        @Override
        public void put(Type value, int x, int y) {
            Map&lt;Integer, Type&gt; rows = values.get(y);
            if (rows == null) {
                rows = new HashMap&lt;Integer, Type&gt;(8);
                values.put(y, rows);
            }
            rows.put(x, value);
        }
    }

Now, we can get started with some initial implementations...
    
    public class DefaultChunkFactory implements ChunkFactory {
        
        private List&lt;Biome&gt; listOfBiomes = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(Biome.values()));
        
        protected List&lt;Biome&gt; getListOfBiomes() {
            return listOfBiomes;
        }
        
        @Override
        public Chunk createChunk(Point worldLocation) {
            List&lt;Biome&gt; biomes = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(getListOfBiomes());
            Collections.shuffle(biomes);
            Biome biome = biomes.get(0);
            return new DefaultChunk(biome, worldLocation);
        }
    }
    
    public class DefaultChunk implements Chunk {        
        private Biome biome;
        private Point location;

        public DefaultChunk(Biome biome, Point location) {
            this.biome = biome;
            this.location = new Point(location);
        }
        
        @Override
        public Biome getBiome() {
            return biome;
        }        

        @Override
        public Point getLocation() {
            return location;
        }
    }
    
    public class DefaultWorld implements World {
        
        private Matrix&lt;Chunk&gt; chunkMatrix = new HashMapMatrix&lt;&gt;();
        private ChunkFactory chunkFactory;

        public DefaultWorld(ChunkFactory chunkFactory) {
            this.chunkFactory = chunkFactory;
        }

        public ChunkFactory getChunkFactory() {
            return chunkFactory;
        }
        
        protected Matrix&lt;Chunk&gt; getChunks() {
            return chunkMatrix;
        }
        
        @Override
        public Chunk getChunkAt(int x, int y) {
            Chunk chunk = getChunks().get(x, y);
            if (chunk == null) {
                chunk = getChunkFactory().createChunk(new Point(x, y));
                getChunks().put(chunk, x, y);
            }
            return chunk;
        }
    }

these are pretty basic, but they build the concept of the &quot;world&quot; and &quot;chunks&quot;.

And finally, we can get start with the UI!

First, a component which can represent a `Chunk`

    public class ChunkPane extends JPanel {
